Renowned economist, Prof. Pat Utomi, has stressed the need to invest in youths to enable them transform the economy. He noted that youths have the capacity to reverse the dwindling fortunes of the economy. Utomi was the keynote speaker at the first International Conference on Innovation, Entrepreneurship and Business Management organised by the University of Lagos Business School (ULBS). It had as theme: “Adapting to business landscape in disruptive times”. “Our country is still challenged. We are the poverty capital of the world. According to a report, in the next 10 years, between us and Congo Democratic Republic,would produce 40 per cent of the world’s poorest people. Thus, we should invest massively in our young people to enable them transform the country and the economy. They have the capacity to change this country for good,” he said.   Osinbajo seeks digitalisation of tax administration     Heritage Bank uses technology to deepen financial inclusion     APC presidential primary and scramble for delegates   The Professor of Political Economy also underscored the importance of deploying technology in deepen entrepreneurship and growth. He said through the tech space Africa would make over $14billion with youths, adding that 60 per cent of the cash would be for Nigeria. Earlier, Vice Chancellor, University of Lagos, Prof. Oluwatoyin Ogundipe lauded the leadership of the ULBS for its performance. He noted that plans were underway to build a mini-refinery for the institution’s Department of Petroleum Engineering. Pioneer Executive Director ULBS, Prof. Abraham Osinubi, said the conference was aimed at halting the disconnect between the academia and industry by creating an interactive avenue for new ideas to solve real life problems. The event also witnessed the launch of the ULBS journal, Lagos Management and Business Review.